& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Incidental findings (IFs) are findings on imaging studies obtained for indications unrelated to the IF. IFs may represent clinically important lesions such as malignancy. However, the vast majority are benign with no clinical relevance. IFs can lead to unnecessary follow-up imaging, procedures, and iatrogenic complications, resulting in significant financial and psychologic burden to patients and the health care system. To address this, the American College of Radiology released a series of white papers that provide management guidelines for a variety of IFs in different organs. Since the original white papers and subsequent updates were published, a wealth of research has been provided on various IFs that is either concordant with or contradictory to previous guidelines. Additionally, there are multiple common IFs that are not discussed in an existing white paper. The authors discuss updated evidence regarding common IFs for various topics including hepatic findings (hyperenhancing liver lesions at CT, echogenic liver lesions), biliary findings (asymptomatic biliary ductal dilatation, focal fundal gallbladder wall thickening, gallbladder polyps), renal findings (indeterminate homogeneous renal mass at CT, hyperechoic renal lesions, hyperintense renal lesions at T1-weighted MRI), adrenal nodules, splenic lesions, bowel and mesenteric findings (intussusception, misty mesentery), and male reproductive findings (testicular microlithiasis, isolated right-sided varicocele). The authors review recent literature that addresses existing white paper topics and common IFs that are not discussed in existing white papers.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2026</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i3" class="graphic" aria-label="Visual abstract containing a key image and key points of the article."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/large/rg.250104.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" aria-labelledby="_i3" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=_i3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.250104">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.250104">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Portal phase CECT shows a hyperenhancing liver lesion consistent with a hemangioma in a low-risk patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig1.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Hyperenhancing liver lesion in a 74-year-old woman who presented with nausea. Axial portal phase CECT image shows a hyperenhancing liver lesion (arrow). In low-risk patients, no follow-up is required. Findings at subsequent MRI (not shown) confirmed a small hemangioma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Portal phase CECT demonstrates peripheral, nodular, discontinuous enhancement of a liver lesion diagnostic of hemangioma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig2.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Enhancing liver lesion in a 55-year-old man who presented with weight loss. Axial portal phase CECT image shows a right liver lobe lesion with peripheral, nodular, and discontinuous hyperenhancement (arrow). If all three of these features are seen at single-phase CECT, the finding can be diagnosed as a hemangioma, and no further follow-up is required. Subsequent MRI findings (not shown) confirmed a hemangioma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Heterogeneously enhancing liver mass on CECT confirmed as hepatic adenoma on MRI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig3.jpg" height="1037" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Heterogeneously enhancing liver mass in a 40-year-old woman with chronic abdominal pain and a history of oral contraceptive use. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows a heterogeneously hyperenhancing hepatic mass (arrow). Follow-up MRI findings (not shown) confirmed this lesion to be consistent with hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Homogeneously hyperechoic liver lesion on ultrasound is consistent with a hemangioma in a low-risk patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig4.jpg" height="1040" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Incidental echogenic liver lesion in a 30-year-old woman who presented with urinary urgency for renal US. Gray-scale US image of the right lobe of the liver shows a homogeneously hyperechoic liver mass (arrow). The finding is compatible with a hemangioma in a patient without risk factors for malignancy, and no follow-up imaging is required.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Peripherally hyperechoic liver lesion on ultrasound showed stability over 4 years, consistent with hemangioma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig5.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Incidental echogenic liver lesion in a 31-year-old woman with abdominal pain. Gray-scale US image of the liver shows an incidental peripherally hyperechoic lesion with an isoechoic center (arrow). This is a classic appearance of a hemangioma. The lesion was stable for over 4 years, compatible with benignity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Hyperechoic liver lesion in a cirrhotic patient was confirmed as HCC on MRI."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig6.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Echogenic liver lesion in a 70-year-old man with metabolic dysfunction–associated steatohepatitis cirrhosis. Gray-scale US image of the liver shows a homogeneously hyperechoic liver mass (arrow). The appearance would be compatible with a hemangioma in a low-risk patient, but given the risk factors in this patient, MRI was performed (not shown) and the findings confirmed HCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Heterogeneously hyperechoic liver lesion in a patient with breast cancer is suspicious for metastasis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig7.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Echogenic liver lesion in an 84-year-old woman with breast cancer who presented with abdominal pain. Gray-scale US image of the liver shows a large heterogeneously hyperechoic liver mass (arrow). The heterogeneous appearance and history of malignancy increase the risk for malignancy in this lesion, which is suspicious for metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Multiple hyperechoic liver lesions in a patient with pancreatic cancer were confirmed as metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig8.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Multiple echogenic liver lesions in a 52-year-old woman with pancreatic adenocarcinoma who presented with right upper quadrant pain. Gray-scale US image of the liver shows multiple homogeneously hyperechoic liver lesions (arrows). These lesions appear similar to hemangiomas. However, in the setting of known malignancy, metastases are possible. Subsequent biopsy of the largest hyperechoic lesion confirmed a diagnosis of metastatic pancreatic adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Gallbladder wall thickening with intramural cysts is consistent with adenomyomatosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig9.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Focal gallbladder wall thickening in a 63-year-old man who presented with epigastric pain. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows focal gallbladder wall thickening with multiple intramural cystic spaces (arrow). This finding is compatible with adenomyomatosis and does not need additional follow-up. Subsequent cholecystectomy findings confirmed a diagnosis of benign adenomyomatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Fundal gallbladder wall thickening stable over time is consistent with benign adenomyomatosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig10.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Focal gallbladder wall thickening in a 76-year-old woman with unintentional weight loss. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows focal fundal gallbladder wall thickening with intramural homogeneous low attenuation (arrow), also compatible with adenomyomatosis. This finding was stable for over 2 years, confirming benignity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Homogeneous gallbladder wall enhancement was suspicious for malignancy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig11.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Focal gallbladder wall thickening in an 83-year-old man with acute pancreatitis. Sagittal portal venous phase CECT image shows homogeneous full-thickness enhancement of the gallbladder fundus (arrow). The findings were suspicious for gallbladder malignancy at follow-up MRI (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="SRU consensus guidelines for gallbladder polyps."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig12.jpg" height="1180" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Diagram shows the Society of Radiologists in Ultrasound (SRU) Gallbladder Polyp Consensus Conference Guidelines. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r37" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r37">37</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Homogeneous low-attenuation renal lesion likely represents a benign hyperdense cyst."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig13.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Indeterminate homogeneous renal mass in a 56-year-old woman with elevated CA 19-9 levels. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows an incidental homogeneous left renal lesion (arrow) that measured 29 HU. According to the current American College of Radiology white paper, MRI would be recommended (<a href="#r11" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r11">11</a>). However, recent data indicate that homogeneous renal masses in this attenuation range at portal venous phase CECT are highly likely to be benign, representing hyperattenuating cysts or cysts with pseudoenhancement, and no follow-up is warranted. Follow-up MRI findings (not shown) confirmed a benign cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Hyperechoic renal lesion on ultrasound was confirmed as angiomyolipoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig14.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Echogenic right renal mass in a 65-year-old woman who presented with upper abdominal pain. Gray-scale US image of the right kidney shows an incidental hyperechoic renal mass (arrow). The most likely diagnosis is angiomyolipoma, but given the size, follow-up CT or MRI is warranted. MRI findings in this case (not shown) confirmed an angiomyolipoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Hyperechoic renal mass without fat on MRI is concerning for RCC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig15.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Indeterminate hyperechoic right renal mass in a 71-year-old man with chronic left lower quadrant pain. Gray-scale US image of the right kidney shows a hyperechoic solid lesion (arrow). Subsequent MRI (not shown) showed an enhancing mass without microscopic or macroscopic fat, which was most concerning for RCC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Non-enhancing hyperintense renal mass on MRI is consistent with a hemorrhagic cyst."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig16.jpg" height="843" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Incidental left renal mass in a 65-year-old man without a significant medical history. <b>(A)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneously hyperintense left renal mass (arrow) with a signal intensity that is more than 2.5 times greater than that in the surrounding renal parenchyma. <b>(B)</b> Axial postcontrast subtraction T1-weighted MR image shows no enhancement of the lesion (arrow). This finding is consistent with a hemorrhagic cyst. Per the updated Bosniak 2019 guidelines, such masses are considered category II.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Homogeneously hypodense splenic lesion confirmed as hemangioma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig17.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Incidental splenic lesion in a 63-year-old woman who presented with left lower quadrant abdominal pain. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows a homogeneously hypoattenuating mass (arrow) in the spleen. Findings at follow-up MRI (not shown) confirmed this to be a splenic hemangioma. In low-risk patients without a history of malignancy and with no constitutional symptoms, this finding does not need further follow-up.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Multiple new splenic lesions in a patient with colon cancer confirmed as metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig18.jpg" height="1086" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Multiple indeterminate splenic lesions in an 82-year-old woman with a history of colon adenocarcinoma who presented with abdominal pain. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows numerous hypoattenuating masses (arrows) within the spleen. Given the patient’s history of malignancy, the findings were most concerning for metastases. A review of CT findings from 4 months earlier (not shown) revealed that these lesions were new, confirming metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Multiple short enteroenteric intussusceptions resolved spontaneously on follow-up."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig19.jpg" height="1034" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Enteroenteric intussusceptions in a 33-year-old man who presented with periumbilical abdominal pain. Coronal portal venous phase CECT image shows three enteroenteric intussusceptions (arrows). These were all shorter than 3.5 cm in length, without an associated small bowel obstruction, wall thickening, or a clear lead point. All three intussusceptions were transient and resolved at follow-up CT 2 days later (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="Enteroenteric intussusception with bowel obstruction was caused by metastatic lung cancer."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig20.jpg" height="987" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Enteroenteric intussusception in a 60-year-old man with a history of lung cancer. Axial portal venous phase CECT image shows an enteroenteric intussusception associated with bowel wall thickening (arrow) and a dilated small bowel compatible with obstruction. The findings are concerning for an underlying lead point. An enhancing mass (arrowhead) is noted in an adjacent small bowel segment. The findings represent metastatic lung cancer to the small bowel, with one mass acting as the lead point for intussusception.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="Colocolic intussusception with enhancing mass was confirmed as colonic adenocarcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig21.jpg" height="1010" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Colocolic intussusception in a 36-year-old man who presented with abdominal discomfort. Coronal portal venous phase CECT image shows a colocolic intussusception (arrow) with an enhancing mass as the lead point (arrowhead). The patient underwent surgical reduction, and pathologic findings revealed colonic adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="Focal misty mesentery without lymphadenopathy is consistent with benign sclerosing mesenteritis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig22.jpg" height="1065" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Misty mesentery in a 66-year-old man with painless hematuria. Axial noncontrast CT image shows a focal region of increased mesenteric fat attenuation (arrow) without associated lymphadenopathy, consistent with sclerosing mesenteritis. Given the lack of lymphadenopathy or a history of malignancy, further follow-up is not required. This patient did not develop malignancy over a 5-year follow-up period, confirming benignity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="Misty mesentery with lymphadenopathy in lymphoma patient requires further evaluation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig23.jpg" height="844" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Misty mesentery in a 41-year-old man with known lymphoma. Axial portal venous phase CECT images show misty mesentery with multiple prominent nonenlarged lymph nodes (arrows in <b>A</b>) and one enlarged lymph node (arrow in <b>B</b>) within the area of increased mesenteric attenuation. Misty mesentery with associated lymphadenopathy requires further evaluation with follow-up imaging, PET/CT, or biopsy, depending on the degree of lymphadenopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic" aria-label="Bilateral testicular microlithiasis without malignancy requires no follow-up in low-risk patients."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.250104/asset/images/rg.250104.fig24.jpg" height="797" width="1065" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Incidental testicular microlithiasis in a 46-year-old man with no significant past medical history and recurrent right testicular pain. Gray-scale US image of the right testicle shows numerous punctate echogenic foci (arrows), compatible with microlithiasis that was also seen in the contralateral testicle (not shown). Over a 2-year follow-up period, the patient did not develop testicular malignancy. Per the American Urological Association guidelines (<a href="#r70" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r70">70</a>), this finding does not require additional follow-up imaging in low-risk patients.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.250104&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Berland LL, Silverman SG, Gore RM, et al. Managing incidental findings on abdominal CT: white paper of the ACR incidental findings committee. <em>J Am Coll Radiol</em> 2010;7(10):754–773.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacr.2010.06.013">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20889105/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Managing+incidental+findings+on+abdominal+CT%3A+white+paper+of+the+ACR+incidental+findings+committee&amp;author=LL+Berland&amp;author=SG+Silverman&amp;author=RM+Gore&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=J+Am+Coll+Radiol&amp;pages=754-773&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jacr.2010.06.013&amp;pmid=20889105">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lumbreras B, Donat L, Hernández-Aguado I. Incidental fi